01:11:20.811 --> 01:11:23.170
Well, actually the next slide is quite similar.

01:11:23.170 --> 01:11:27.491
So another way to think of this

01:11:27.491 --> 01:11:29.491
is that the client, that's us,

01:11:29.491 --> 01:11:31.691
we can do things the assistant can't do.

01:11:32.050 --> 01:11:34.010
We can go get the weather.

01:11:34.010 --> 01:11:37.290
So tools let us take these capabilities,

01:11:37.290 --> 01:11:38.491
whatever capabilities we want,

01:11:38.491 --> 01:11:41.170
and we put control into the hands of the assistant

01:11:41.170 --> 01:11:43.010
so that it decides when to use them.

01:11:43.010 --> 01:11:44.730
It decides what arguments to pass in.

01:11:44.730 --> 01:11:46.770
It decides what to do with the results.

01:11:46.770 --> 01:11:48.330
And having this ability,

01:11:48.330 --> 01:11:51.091
like having it coordinate tools

01:11:51.091 --> 01:11:52.491
that we create and implement,

01:11:52.491 --> 01:11:54.890
it is surprisingly general.

01:11:54.890 --> 01:11:57.411
It's surprisingly powerful.

01:11:57.411 --> 01:11:58.971
Just to give you an example,

01:11:59.971 --> 01:12:04.730
so in our home, we use the Amazon Alexa assistant

01:12:04.730 --> 01:12:07.651
to control the lights, to set alarms and kitchen timers

01:12:07.651 --> 01:12:09.251
and things like that.

01:12:09.251 --> 01:12:11.651
And a couple of years ago,

01:12:11.651 --> 01:12:13.850
there was a set of news reports came out

01:12:13.850 --> 01:12:15.450
saying that Alexa was losing

01:12:15.450 --> 01:12:17.010
enormous amounts of money for Amazon.

01:12:17.010 --> 01:12:19.531
They've never figured out a business case for it.

01:12:19.531 --> 01:12:22.610
And I thought to myself like, okay, if Alexa went away,

01:12:22.610 --> 01:12:26.251
how difficult would it be to replace it?

01:12:26.251 --> 01:12:27.651
How difficult would it be for me

01:12:28.050 --> 01:12:31.050
to build my own Raspberry Pi version of Alexa?

01:12:31.050 --> 01:12:33.691
And other than the microphone technology,

01:12:33.691 --> 01:12:35.010
the most challenging thing would be

01:12:35.010 --> 01:12:38.211
how do you take natural language speech

01:12:38.211 --> 01:12:40.170
and turn it into intent,

01:12:40.170 --> 01:12:42.890
turn it into programmatic intent

01:12:42.890 --> 01:12:45.251
that my scripts can use to say,

01:12:45.251 --> 01:12:46.811
okay, I better go turn the lights on

01:12:46.811 --> 01:12:49.371
or open the garage door or what have you.

01:12:50.850 --> 01:12:53.330
And if you think of all of the capabilities

01:12:53.330 --> 01:12:55.570
that Alexa has as just being things

01:12:55.570 --> 01:12:57.811
that you can implement using tool calls,

01:12:57.811 --> 01:12:59.691
well, then the hardest part of Alexa

01:12:59.691 --> 01:13:02.091
is now a solved problem.

01:13:02.091 --> 01:13:03.890
Like all you have to do is have a tool

01:13:03.890 --> 01:13:05.691
that turns lights on and off.

01:13:05.691 --> 01:13:09.610
And then you put the query that came from the user,

01:13:09.610 --> 01:13:11.491
you just give it to the LLM and say,

01:13:11.491 --> 01:13:15.010
and here are the tools that you can call if you want to.

01:13:15.010 --> 01:13:18.131
What used to be the hardest part is now,

01:13:19.811 --> 01:13:22.610
half a cent per query or something like that.

01:13:22.850 --> 01:13:25.691
And it just is the easiest thing to implement.

01:13:25.691 --> 01:13:29.610
So it's an incredibly powerful capability.

01:13:29.610 --> 01:13:31.730
And that example also points out

01:13:31.730 --> 01:13:33.730
an interesting thing about tools.

01:13:33.730 --> 01:13:35.931
They don't only have to be a way

01:13:35.931 --> 01:13:39.251
to get more information into the model.

01:13:39.251 --> 01:13:41.890
They can also be a way to let the model

01:13:41.890 --> 01:13:45.050
exert force into the universe.

01:13:45.050 --> 01:13:49.290
It can be tools that are not just for the value they return,

01:13:49.290 --> 01:13:52.371
but tools that operate for their side effects,

01:13:53.131 --> 01:13:54.971
for the effect that they have on the world.

01:13:54.971 --> 01:13:57.290
So turning lights on and off is one example,

01:13:57.290 --> 01:14:01.290
but it could be sending an email or sending a Slack alert.

01:14:01.290 --> 01:14:04.570
It could be putting a row in a database.

01:14:04.570 --> 01:14:06.931
It could be, as in the case of query chat,

01:14:06.931 --> 01:14:09.570
updating the shiny application

01:14:09.570 --> 01:14:11.290
that you're sitting right next to.

01:14:12.450 --> 01:14:14.531
We really have to think expansively,

01:14:14.531 --> 01:14:16.371
like anything you can do with a function,

01:14:16.371 --> 01:14:19.770
pretty much an assistant can now do.

01:14:20.651 --> 01:14:23.931
So this is the illustration I came up with

01:14:23.931 --> 01:14:27.891
with ChachiBT over the last day or so,

01:14:27.891 --> 01:14:31.371
that an LLM by itself is very wise,

01:14:31.371 --> 01:14:32.210
but it's just sitting there.

01:14:32.210 --> 01:14:36.530
So I use an elephant because Elmer's logo is an elephant.

01:14:36.530 --> 01:14:39.730
An LLM with system prompt customizations is kind of cool.

01:14:39.730 --> 01:14:41.891
Like you can dress it up how you want

01:14:41.891 --> 01:14:43.970
and make it act the way you want.

01:14:43.970 --> 01:14:46.331
But an LLM with tool calls is like,

01:14:46.331 --> 01:14:49.451
it's got all these things on that can do incredible things

01:14:50.131 --> 01:14:52.931
that it could not do without it, so.

01:14:57.650 --> 01:15:00.290
Yeah, Martin says a bit scary, the third one.

