I work on Shiny, I work on Elmer, I give talks

01:24:11.171 --> 01:24:15.491
and it frequently will kind of bias answers

01:24:16.411 --> 01:24:20.210
pretty severely towards what I actually care about.

01:24:20.210 --> 01:24:22.371
Or for personal things like,

01:24:24.251 --> 01:24:26.810
I have an old Mazda sports car

01:24:26.850 --> 01:24:30.570
that I do a lot of talking with Claude about,

01:24:30.570 --> 01:24:32.011
sorry, with ChatGBT about,

01:24:32.011 --> 01:24:37.011
and it's able to, if I ask it about secondary turbochargers,

01:24:37.810 --> 01:24:39.891
it usually knows, like it knows exactly,

01:24:39.891 --> 01:24:41.531
but I'm talking about my car.

01:24:41.531 --> 01:24:46.531
So it is very useful, but a little scary.

01:24:56.810 --> 01:25:01.810
Sorry, not sure how Python got in there.

01:25:26.810 --> 01:25:27.651
Okay.

01:25:48.771 --> 01:25:51.610
I guess just with the three minutes remaining in the break,

01:25:51.610 --> 01:25:54.011
for those of you who are not running R

01:25:54.011 --> 01:25:59.011
and not following along with the code for whatever reason,

01:25:59.051 --> 01:26:02.771
I'll just go ahead and show you this quiz example

01:26:02.771 --> 01:26:04.531
that I asked you to take a look at.

01:26:06.891 --> 01:26:10.051
So this is a little quiz game.

01:26:13.051 --> 01:26:17.210
I have a tool here called play sound,

01:26:17.210 --> 01:26:18.970
and it plays one of three sounds,

01:26:18.970 --> 01:26:21.131
correct, incorrect, or you win.

01:26:22.131 --> 01:26:24.970
And I've mapped those to three particular sounds

01:26:24.970 --> 01:26:26.651
in the BPAR package.

01:26:29.891 --> 01:26:34.891
And here I've created an Elmer chat object,

01:26:35.850 --> 01:26:38.570
but the system prompt was enough

01:26:38.570 --> 01:26:40.730
that instead of putting a string here,

01:26:40.730 --> 01:26:42.771
I put it in a separate markdown file.

01:26:42.771 --> 01:26:46.210
And this is a pattern I highly recommend people follow.

01:26:47.210 --> 01:26:52.210
So this entire markdown file will be passed as a string

01:26:52.251 --> 01:26:55.651
to the Elmer chat object.

01:26:55.651 --> 01:26:57.450
So I'm saying it's a quiz game show,

01:26:58.411 --> 01:27:00.090
ask the user to choose a theme.

01:27:01.251 --> 01:27:03.291
I'm saying ask simple questions,

01:27:03.291 --> 01:27:06.210
ask user to answer via multiple choice.

01:27:06.210 --> 01:27:09.411
And the most important thing here says play sound effects.

01:27:11.330 --> 01:27:13.291
And then I give it an example of like,

01:27:14.251 --> 01:27:17.131
you know, I actually don't think that this is necessary,

01:27:19.570 --> 01:27:22.491
but it was with the, you know,

01:27:22.491 --> 01:27:24.970
nine months ago when I made this example,

01:27:24.970 --> 01:27:29.171
this really helped it behave the way I wanted it to.

01:27:29.171 --> 01:27:33.450
So I'll go ahead and run this.

01:27:38.730 --> 01:27:40.491
Okay, welcome to this quiz show.

01:27:44.291 --> 01:27:49.131
Let's do history.

01:27:54.251 --> 01:27:57.810
Okay, what year did World War II end?

01:27:57.810 --> 01:28:02.090
So let me say B.

01:28:05.251 --> 01:28:08.330
So it's correct, so hopefully you heard that sound.

01:28:08.330 --> 01:28:10.371
And then if I get something wrong,

01:28:14.291 --> 01:28:15.651
it plays a different sound.

01:28:18.371 --> 01:28:20.051
And if you get all the way to the end,

01:28:20.051 --> 01:28:22.651
then it plays kind of a fanfare for you.

01:28:24.930 --> 01:28:29.411
So just like totally in contrast to the weather example,

01:28:31.011 --> 01:28:33.850
there's no useful information coming back

01:28:33.850 --> 01:28:35.690
from this tool at all.

01:28:35.690 --> 01:28:38.771
It's just about making something happen in this case,

01:28:38.771 --> 01:28:41.210
making the sound, the sound happen.

01:28:43.291 --> 01:28:48.291
Okay, great, hopefully we're all back.

01:28:52.771 --> 01:28:54.930
This Elmer package is remarkable, thanks.

01:28:54.930 --> 01:28:57.251
Can it be used for retrieval augmented generation?

01:28:57.251 --> 01:29:01.090
So there, I'm gonna mention it now

01:29:01.090 --> 01:29:04.051
because I don't really mention it later.

01:29:04.051 --> 01:29:05.771
Well, actually, no, I'm gonna hold on.

01:29:05.771 --> 01:29:08.090
I'm gonna talk about retrieval augmented generation

01:29:08.090 --> 01:29:08.930
in a second.

01:29:09.930 --> 01:29:14.930
Okay, but before that, we talked about tool calling.

01:29:14.930 --> 01:29:18.411
Let's talk about model context protocol or MCP.

01:29:19.491 --> 01:29:24.330
This has been a real buzzword in the news lately.

01:29:24.330 --> 01:29:26.930
We've heard all about MCP this and MCP that.

01:29:27.891 --> 01:29:32.131
You can think of MCP as a standard way

01:29:32.131 --> 01:29:36.970
to make tools available to LLMs without writing more code.

01:29:37.810 --> 01:29:42.011
So we use tools in this way.

01:29:42.011 --> 01:29:44.771
It's like pretty easy to do, but you are writing code.

01:29:45.651 --> 01:29:49.291
Whereas MCP is like the same capabilities.

01:29:49.291 --> 01:29:52.011
It is based on tool calling,

01:29:52.011 --> 01:29:55.531
but instead of you writing code to wire up the tool,

01:29:55.531 --> 01:29:59.570
you're just like snapping them together like Lego bricks.

01:30:01.090 --> 01:30:06.090
So there are MCP servers that provide tools,

01:30:06.970 --> 01:30:08.171
like there's a Google Maps tool,

01:30:08.171 --> 01:30:11.210
there's a file system tool and a browser MCP.

01:30:13.491 --> 01:30:18.491
And then you have the LLMs are in these applications

01:30:20.690 --> 01:30:24.051
like Cloud Desktop, Cloud Code, these other programs.

01:30:24.051 --> 01:30:26.930
Copilot now supports MCPs.

01:30:26.930 --> 01:30:30.531
So without writing any code to bring together

01:30:30.531 --> 01:30:32.171
Google Maps and Cloud Code,

01:30:32.171 --> 01:30:35.090
instead you can just use like a configuration file to say,

01:30:35.090 --> 01:30:38.051
I've got my Google Map MCP over here.

01:30:38.051 --> 01:30:40.771
Cloud Code has a configuration file over here.

01:30:40.771 --> 01:30:42.850
Just stick the two together.

01:30:44.330 --> 01:30:45.810
So that's one advantage is that

01:30:45.810 --> 01:30:46.891
you don't have to write code.

01:30:46.891 --> 01:30:49.531
You just have to be able to edit a YAML file

01:30:49.531 --> 01:30:50.450
or something like that,

01:30:50.450 --> 01:30:55.090
which means it puts this kind of LLM customization

01:30:55.090 --> 01:30:57.011
in the hands of way more people.

01:30:58.251 --> 01:31:01.690
Honestly, to me, I find it a little bit scary how easy,

01:31:01.690 --> 01:31:05.491
like we are talking about two very powerful tools here,

01:31:05.491 --> 01:31:07.610
arbitrary access to your file system

01:31:07.610 --> 01:31:09.850
and then control over a web browser.

01:31:09.850 --> 01:31:12.810
And we're saying now anyone can combine these two things

01:31:12.810 --> 01:31:15.051
with any chat front end.

01:31:15.051 --> 01:31:17.291
You don't even need to know how to code.

01:31:17.291 --> 01:31:19.251
Where I'm a little bit like,

01:31:19.251 --> 01:31:20.570
maybe you should know how to code

01:31:20.570 --> 01:31:25.570
if you're gonna equip the LLM with such powerful tools.

01:31:26.771 --> 01:31:30.411
So the other thing it does is it very conveniently,

01:31:30.411 --> 01:31:32.411
it provides a convenient way

01:31:32.411 --> 01:31:34.930
for you to write tools in one language

01:31:34.930 --> 01:31:37.371
and then consume them in another.

01:31:37.371 --> 01:31:40.131
So maybe like it's really easy to create

01:31:40.131 --> 01:31:42.850
a Google Maps tool in JavaScript

01:31:42.850 --> 01:31:46.491
because Google Maps has a really good JavaScript SDK.

01:31:46.491 --> 01:31:51.491
But when you're reading data from Databricks,

01:31:51.771 --> 01:31:53.651
then you really wanna use Python

01:31:53.651 --> 01:31:56.051
or you really want to have access

01:31:56.051 --> 01:31:59.930
to like generalized linear models,

01:31:59.930 --> 01:32:01.850
then you wanna use an R-based tool.

01:32:01.850 --> 01:32:06.850
And MCP really helps provide like a neutral mechanism

01:32:08.210 --> 01:32:11.690
for combining tools implemented in all different languages.

01:32:11.690 --> 01:32:15.610
There's more that MCPs do, but that's the gist of it.

01:32:15.610 --> 01:32:17.610
And I start with tool calling

01:32:17.610 --> 01:32:19.210
because I think tool calling gives you

01:32:19.210 --> 01:32:21.330
the mental model you need to understand

01:32:21.330 --> 01:32:24.251
like model context protocol is just a convenient way

01:32:24.251 --> 01:32:26.011
to implement tool calling.

01:32:26.011 --> 01:32:28.171
But what is happening underneath is the same thing.

01:32:28.171 --> 01:32:31.610
You are giving the model a description of tools

01:32:31.610 --> 01:32:34.251
that are then executed locally,

01:32:34.251 --> 01:32:35.970
whether directly in an R function

01:32:35.970 --> 01:32:39.330
or calling out to one of these model context protocol things.

01:32:40.171 --> 01:32:42.810
It's all the same.

01:32:42.810 --> 01:32:44.771
As far as the LLM interaction is concerned,

01:32:44.771 --> 01:32:46.171
it's exactly the same thing.

01:32:48.011 --> 01:32:48.850
Okay.

01:32:49.891 --> 01:32:51.371
Someone had mentioned MCP before.

01:32:51.371 --> 01:32:54.891
I hope that answered whatever question they may have had.

01:32:54.891 --> 01:32:57.330
Any other questions about MCPs before we move on?

01:32:58.171 --> 01:32:59.011
Okay.

01:33:05.011 --> 01:33:08.970
Elmer has had tool calling support since the beginning.

01:33:08.970 --> 01:33:10.930
I can't remember right now

01:33:10.930 --> 01:33:14.771
whether we have added model context protocol support

01:33:14.771 --> 01:33:16.810
directly to it yet.

01:33:16.810 --> 01:33:20.371
But if not, that is something that'll come soon.

01:33:20.371 --> 01:33:24.011
Scary as it is, we are going to make it something

01:33:24.011 --> 01:33:25.771
that people can do if they want to.

01:33:29.171 --> 01:33:30.011
Okay.

01:33:31.330 --> 01:33:33.850
So that's the end of our tool calling MCP,

01:33:35.051 --> 01:33:40.051
strap weapons to an LLM kind of part of the workshop.

01:33:40.450 --> 01:33:42.610
Now we're going to completely shift gears

01:33:42.610 --> 01:33:45.171
to talk about the different models that are available

01:33:45.171 --> 01:33:47.491
and how we choose between them, okay?

01:33:49.011 --> 01:33:51.970
So there are many models out there.

01:33:53.651 --> 01:33:57.450
There are way more than I could possibly name,

01:33:57.730 --> 01:33:59.570
but there's a smaller number of ones

01:33:59.570 --> 01:34:04.210
that are like relevant to many of us.

01:34:04.210 --> 01:34:07.210
And five of the ones that we're choosing to focus on here,

01:34:07.210 --> 01:34:11.291
OpenAI, Anthropics Cloud, Google Gemini,

01:34:11.291 --> 01:34:13.210
MetaLlama, DeepSeek.

01:34:13.210 --> 01:34:14.610
We'll talk a little bit about each of these.

01:34:14.610 --> 01:34:17.970
There's one that's, there are a few that are missing

01:34:17.970 --> 01:34:21.570
that I, you know, arguably should be on this slide.

01:34:21.570 --> 01:34:25.291
Mistral is one, M-I-S-T-R-A-L.

01:34:25.291 --> 01:34:29.610
They're probably the leading European OpenWeights model.

01:34:29.610 --> 01:34:32.930
And then a bunch of other ones besides DeepSeek from China,

01:34:32.930 --> 01:34:35.450
like Quen and some other ones.

01:34:38.651 --> 01:34:40.051
Thanks for joining us, Ella.

01:34:41.011 --> 01:34:42.411
Hope that was useful so far.

01:34:43.411 --> 01:34:45.850
So we'll go in a little bit of depth for each of these,

01:34:45.850 --> 01:34:47.531
but not too much.

01:34:47.531 --> 01:34:50.690
Probably the most widely known and widely used models

01:34:50.690 --> 01:34:52.891
right now are the ones from OpenAI.

01:34:52.891 --> 01:34:57.891
GBT 4.1 is their kind of best general purpose model,

01:34:57.891 --> 01:34:59.411
and it is extremely good.

01:34:59.411 --> 01:35:00.930
I've put stars next to the ones

01:35:00.930 --> 01:35:05.810
that are particularly highly recommended by, well, by me.

01:35:05.810 --> 01:35:07.891
So GBT 4.1 is excellent.

01:35:07.891 --> 01:35:11.251
And then they have cheaper versions called GBT 4.1 Mini

01:35:11.251 --> 01:35:15.330
and GBT 4.1 Nano that are quite a bit cheaper.

01:35:15.330 --> 01:35:18.210
They do change the equation enough

01:35:18.210 --> 01:35:20.330
that it might change what you are willing

01:35:20.330 --> 01:35:21.810
to use these models for.

01:35:23.171 --> 01:35:25.210
I believe they're pretty much equivalent in feature set.

01:35:25.210 --> 01:35:27.210
They're just like different amounts of,

01:35:28.291 --> 01:35:29.730
I don't want to use the word intelligence,

01:35:29.730 --> 01:35:34.730
but reliability, adherence to instructions,

01:35:35.051 --> 01:35:36.690
good use of tool calling, that kind of thing.

01:35:36.690 --> 01:35:39.610
Gets worse as you get faster and cheaper.

01:35:39.610 --> 01:35:40.970
On the other end of the spectrum,

01:35:40.970 --> 01:35:42.570
you have a set of reasoning models

01:35:42.570 --> 01:35:44.330
that begin with the letter O.

01:35:44.330 --> 01:35:49.051
So O3 is, before it responds,

01:35:49.051 --> 01:35:52.090
it will sort of like, quote unquote, think to itself.

01:35:52.090 --> 01:35:55.131
It'll talk to itself and sort of talk itself

01:35:55.131 --> 01:35:57.051
into and out of different answers

01:35:57.051 --> 01:35:59.610
before it responds to you with an official response.

01:35:59.610 --> 01:36:02.810
And it turns out that this is actually

01:36:02.810 --> 01:36:07.810
a pretty useful capability for certain types of problems.

01:36:08.210 --> 01:36:10.411
The way I think of it is,

01:36:10.411 --> 01:36:12.131
it's not an analogy that'll land with everybody,

01:36:12.131 --> 01:36:15.690
but if you have read the, what is that book?

01:36:15.690 --> 01:36:18.051
Thinking Fast and Slow.

01:36:20.090 --> 01:36:21.330
Is it Kahneman?

01:36:21.651 --> 01:36:24.291
Anyway, that famous book, Thinking Fast and Slow,

01:36:24.291 --> 01:36:28.251
that says like human brains operate in two modes.

01:36:28.251 --> 01:36:30.051
There's like mode one,

01:36:30.051 --> 01:36:32.411
where you just are thinking almost

01:36:32.411 --> 01:36:34.131
like pattern matching and reflex,

01:36:34.131 --> 01:36:36.810
where you just like immediately respond to something.

01:36:38.131 --> 01:36:39.411
That's system one.

01:36:39.411 --> 01:36:41.131
And that is something we can do

01:36:41.131 --> 01:36:43.651
like surprisingly effectively as human beings.

01:36:44.891 --> 01:36:47.970
We can do it very quickly, it requires very little energy.

01:36:47.970 --> 01:36:50.090
And when we are doing things

01:36:50.090 --> 01:36:52.531
that we are sort of used to,

01:36:52.531 --> 01:36:55.210
then we do this almost without thinking.

01:36:56.090 --> 01:36:58.570
System two is where you kind of stop

01:36:58.570 --> 01:37:01.371
and weigh different criteria.

01:37:01.371 --> 01:37:03.251
You really kind of use your,

01:37:05.011 --> 01:37:06.131
I didn't make it that far into the book,

01:37:06.131 --> 01:37:09.171
but you're really using your brain harder,

01:37:09.171 --> 01:37:11.090
you're thinking more deliberately.

01:37:11.090 --> 01:37:14.491
And system two, like the second mode of thinking

01:37:14.491 --> 01:37:17.011
is better for overcoming your natural biases

01:37:17.011 --> 01:37:19.011
and things like that.

01:37:19.011 --> 01:37:20.970
And I don't know if this is a great analogy,

01:37:20.970 --> 01:37:22.651
but I think it's at least a good analogy

01:37:22.651 --> 01:37:24.450
that like these models,

01:37:24.450 --> 01:37:26.291
like generally you can think of them

01:37:26.291 --> 01:37:27.771
as working in system one,

01:37:27.771 --> 01:37:31.491
and these models have a remarkable system one.

01:37:31.491 --> 01:37:33.610
And O3 is like system two,

01:37:33.610 --> 01:37:35.690
where it's really forcing itself to slow down

01:37:35.690 --> 01:37:36.810
and really think about things

01:37:36.810 --> 01:37:38.771
before just beginning to answer.

01:37:40.411 --> 01:37:42.450
At the time that this slide was written,

01:37:42.450 --> 01:37:45.610
or even as recently as yesterday,

01:37:45.810 --> 01:37:48.970
O3 was quite a bit more expensive than GPT-4.1.

01:37:48.970 --> 01:37:53.210
I think this morning they announced a 80% price decrease.

01:37:53.210 --> 01:37:57.491
So it is now the same price per token as GPT-4.1.

01:37:57.491 --> 01:38:00.891
It is slower, it is still for,

01:38:00.891 --> 01:38:01.850
I think for a lot of things

01:38:01.850 --> 01:38:03.810
you're gonna wanna use the general model,

01:38:03.810 --> 01:38:08.051
but this is not nearly as expensive as it used to be.

01:38:08.051 --> 01:38:10.051
And then there is O4 mini,

01:38:10.051 --> 01:38:11.570
which is like the next generation,

01:38:11.570 --> 01:38:14.011
but smaller model that does reasoning.

01:38:14.011 --> 01:38:16.771
And this is particularly beloved right now,

01:38:16.771 --> 01:38:19.491
especially for problem solving and coding.

01:38:21.291 --> 01:38:23.891
You can access OpenAI models

01:38:23.891 --> 01:38:27.291
either through OpenAI themselves or through Azure.

01:38:27.291 --> 01:38:30.531
A lot of corporations and organizations

01:38:30.531 --> 01:38:34.210
that are already all the way in with Azure

01:38:34.210 --> 01:38:35.570
prefer to use Azure

01:38:35.570 --> 01:38:38.610
because they make a more specific set

01:38:38.610 --> 01:38:41.531
of security and privacy guarantees.

01:38:42.051 --> 01:38:45.970
I don't know if these are gonna be at all usable

01:38:45.970 --> 01:38:50.171
to those of you working with patient data,

01:38:50.171 --> 01:38:52.690
but I have to believe like these.

01:38:49.115 --> 01:38:53.595
I don't know if these are going to be at all usable to, you know, those of you working

01:38:53.595 --> 01:38:59.275
with, you know, patient data, but I have to believe like these, these are going to be

01:38:59.275 --> 01:39:03.635
solved problems at some point, like the stakes are so high, and there's so many companies

01:39:03.635 --> 01:39:08.135
with incentives to make these tools work for all different kinds of scenarios, including

01:39:08.135 --> 01:39:16.155
incredibly sensitive PII and PHI scenarios that I am sure if Azure does not already,

01:39:16.155 --> 01:39:21.515
they will be offering like here is the highest security that we can offer, we're going to,

01:39:21.515 --> 01:39:27.275
we're going to take OpenAI's largest models and stick them in a very, very restrictive

01:39:27.275 --> 01:39:31.795
sandbox for you, you know, that's HIPAA compliant and whatever, I just, I can't believe that's

01:39:31.795 --> 01:39:33.995
not going to happen.

01:39:33.995 --> 01:39:40.515
But that is by no means advice for how to use these models today, I have no idea what

01:39:40.515 --> 01:39:46.394
the, what the implications are for, for, for health information.

01:39:46.394 --> 01:39:54.835
Okay, so the second, and my personal favorite are the Anthropic models.

01:39:54.835 --> 01:40:00.354
So Claude Sonnet is the equivalent of like GPT 4.1.

01:40:00.354 --> 01:40:06.754
It is amazing for code generation, and I think most of the people I know treat this as their

01:40:06.754 --> 01:40:12.034
sort of the best daily driver for like technical things.

01:40:12.034 --> 01:40:18.275
Claude Sonnet 4 is their most recent model, but 3.7 and 3.5 were the last two versions,

01:40:18.275 --> 01:40:23.555
and they're both still excellent for their own different reasons.

01:40:23.555 --> 01:40:27.835
These four, 3.5, 3.7, and 4, have slightly different personalities.

01:40:27.835 --> 01:40:32.555
3.7 and 4 try a lot harder to answer questions than 3.5.

01:40:32.555 --> 01:40:35.835
For example, if they're writing code and they realize they made a mistake, they will try

01:40:35.835 --> 01:40:40.915
over and over to correct these mistakes, where 3.5 gives up a little bit more easily.

01:40:40.915 --> 01:40:43.195
Sometimes that's good, sometimes that's bad.

01:40:43.195 --> 01:40:49.115
But all, all three of those versions of Sonnet are really excellent models.

01:40:49.115 --> 01:40:52.915
Claude Opus 4 is supposed to be stronger than Sonnet 4.

01:40:52.915 --> 01:40:59.075
I have not really seen a ton of evidence that it is actually better, but it is definitely

01:40:59.075 --> 01:41:00.115
expensive and slower.

01:41:00.115 --> 01:41:04.034
So I default to Sonnet.

01:41:04.034 --> 01:41:08.594
And then there is a cheaper version of Claude 3.5 called Haiku.

01:41:08.594 --> 01:41:13.674
I'm not sure why, but there's no 3.7 or 4 of Haiku yet.

01:41:13.674 --> 01:41:15.794
It is a little bit faster, and it is a little bit cheaper.

01:41:15.794 --> 01:41:19.234
I think it's a third of the price of Sonnet.

01:41:19.234 --> 01:41:25.335
So it's not 10 times cheaper, it's not 20 times cheaper, it's just a third of the price.

01:41:25.335 --> 01:41:30.594
Similar to OpenAI, you can get access to Anthropx models either through Anthropx itself or through

01:41:30.594 --> 01:41:32.715
AWS Bedrock.

01:41:32.715 --> 01:41:33.915
Actually this list is incomplete.

01:41:34.794 --> 01:41:43.234
You can also get access through Google has a Vertex offering that has Claude access.

01:41:43.234 --> 01:41:48.555
So if your organization uses a lot of Google, that might be an option.

01:41:48.555 --> 01:41:54.874
Databricks and Snowflake also both have options for getting access to Claude.

01:41:54.874 --> 01:41:59.195
And I think at this point, people who use these models a lot will say that these are

01:41:59.195 --> 01:42:01.394
the best models for code generation.

01:42:01.394 --> 01:42:06.594
There are benchmarks out there that at different times have had Claude, Sonnet not ranked at

01:42:06.594 --> 01:42:07.794
the top.

01:42:07.794 --> 01:42:12.995
I just don't believe them, and a lot of people have expressed this, that when the benchmarks

01:42:12.995 --> 01:42:18.555
disagree with your personal experience, be skeptical of the benchmarks.

01:42:18.555 --> 01:42:24.754
They have been shown to be gained pretty heavily over the past year.

01:42:24.754 --> 01:42:26.995
Feel free to ask questions at any point during this.

01:42:26.995 --> 01:42:30.874
I'm going to go on for a little bit about this.

01:42:30.874 --> 01:42:34.594
The Google models, I have to admit, I have very little experience with them, but people

01:42:34.594 --> 01:42:43.514
that I trust have said that both the latest Gemini 2.5 Flash, which is their faster, cheaper

01:42:43.514 --> 01:42:50.995
one, and Gemini 2.5 Pro, which is their smarter, slower one, that both of them are really excellent

01:42:50.995 --> 01:42:51.995
models.

01:42:51.995 --> 01:42:54.314
They have very large context lengths.

01:42:54.314 --> 01:43:03.115
And Google also, I think their cheaper models are very cheap.

01:43:03.115 --> 01:43:10.275
So that covers what we think are the three most important families of proprietary hosted

01:43:10.275 --> 01:43:11.275
models.

01:43:11.275 --> 01:43:13.555
Like, these models, you cannot download these models.

01:43:13.555 --> 01:43:18.634
You can only access them through APIs that you pay for.

01:43:18.634 --> 01:43:22.954
Now there's another set of models that you can download and run them.

01:43:22.954 --> 01:43:24.074
You can run them on your laptop.

01:43:24.074 --> 01:43:27.914
If you have a powerful enough laptop, you can deploy them on a server.

01:43:27.914 --> 01:43:36.875
You can take these models and build your own derivations on top of them.

01:43:36.875 --> 01:43:41.514
And the most famous of these is Llama, which is from Meta.

01:43:41.514 --> 01:43:48.555
So Llama itself is just, like, many, many gigabytes of numbers.

01:43:48.555 --> 01:43:52.354
So in order to actually run it, in order to turn it into an API that you can call using

01:43:52.354 --> 01:43:55.354
Elmer, you need something to host it with.

01:43:55.354 --> 01:43:59.074
And the most popular of those is called Ollama.

01:43:59.074 --> 01:44:02.555
So this is an open source piece of software that you can download.

01:44:02.555 --> 01:44:09.234
And then they have a repository of different models that it's very, very easy.

01:44:09.234 --> 01:44:17.954
You just, like, if you wanted to use Llama 4, then you would just say Ollama run Llama

01:44:17.954 --> 01:44:25.194
4, and that would automatically download and serve up this model.

01:44:25.194 --> 01:44:30.555
There are several different versions and sizes of these models.

01:44:30.555 --> 01:44:35.715
The large ones surprisingly are pretty, sorry, supposedly, the largest ones supposedly are

01:44:35.715 --> 01:44:41.074
pretty smart, but there is no way you're going to run this model on your own hardware, your

01:44:41.074 --> 01:44:42.835
own personal hardware.

01:44:42.835 --> 01:44:48.115
These require enormous GPUs that are, you know, tens of thousands of dollars, and you

01:44:48.115 --> 01:44:54.835
need to use, like, a bunch of them in parallel to serve up one API endpoint for the best

01:44:54.835 --> 01:44:55.835
models.

01:44:55.835 --> 01:44:59.514
And even at their best, they're not quite as good as the best that OpenAI and Anthropic

01:44:59.514 --> 01:45:01.835
and Google have to offer.

01:45:01.835 --> 01:45:04.995
The Llama models are free, yes.

01:45:04.995 --> 01:45:09.875
However, there are several smaller versions that they have made available at different

01:45:09.875 --> 01:45:19.354
times that are faster, easier to run, dumber, and those are all available and free to download

01:45:19.354 --> 01:45:20.674
as well.

01:45:20.674 --> 01:45:24.035
I'm not going to say much more about this, but suffice to say, you can really go deep

01:45:24.035 --> 01:45:25.194
into this world.

01:45:25.194 --> 01:45:32.234
There are things like quantizing, which is a technique for taking a 95 parameter 90 billion

01:45:32.234 --> 01:45:35.875
parameter model and making it effectively a smaller model while retaining most of the

01:45:35.875 --> 01:45:36.875
intelligence.

01:45:36.875 --> 01:45:40.875
These are all techniques that you can get into if you look into how to run these things

01:45:40.875 --> 01:45:42.715
locally.

01:45:42.715 --> 01:45:49.155
I will warn you that these models are just not as good as the ones that you've been using

01:45:49.155 --> 01:45:50.835
today.

01:45:50.835 --> 01:45:55.354
I really encourage people, unless you have a really good reason, start with the best

01:45:55.354 --> 01:45:56.354
models.

01:45:56.354 --> 01:45:58.035
Start with the frontier models.

01:45:58.035 --> 01:46:02.995
It'll show you kind of what is capable, and then I think we can all assume that these

01:46:02.995 --> 01:46:06.074
sort of lesser models will get better over time.

01:46:06.155 --> 01:46:09.995
If the only problem with what you've done is that it's running on Claude and you can't

01:46:09.995 --> 01:46:17.035
deploy it locally, probably within the next year or two, hopefully, you will be able to

01:46:17.035 --> 01:46:22.914
run it locally on some kind of smaller model.

01:46:22.914 --> 01:46:23.914
Also great for airplanes.

01:46:23.914 --> 01:46:29.155
I keep OLAMA around with a local model just so that when I'm on an airplane, I can still

01:46:29.155 --> 01:46:35.354
have a coding assistant to chat with.

01:46:35.634 --> 01:46:38.875
Alex Ziskin, YouTube channel, if you want to nerd on the quantization and check some

01:46:38.875 --> 01:46:41.194
comparison on hardware for LLM, awesome.

01:46:41.194 --> 01:46:42.194
Thank you for that.

01:46:42.194 --> 01:46:43.194
Thank you for that, Zoom user.

01:46:43.194 --> 01:46:45.954
Oh, I'm sorry, there's other things.

01:46:45.954 --> 01:46:50.835
Gemini has strengths in conversational AI apps, fast, real-time interactions, very natural.

01:46:50.835 --> 01:46:51.835
Thank you.

01:46:51.835 --> 01:46:54.835
That's really great feedback.

01:46:54.835 --> 01:47:01.474
Is it also true for running models for research, like NLP?

01:47:01.474 --> 01:47:03.835
Let's come back to that at the end.

01:47:03.835 --> 01:47:07.234
Well, no, let's talk about that now.

01:47:07.234 --> 01:47:11.074
I am not an expert in this by any means.

01:47:11.074 --> 01:47:19.954
But for NLP, if you're using LLMs for NLP for things like sentiment analysis or classification

01:47:19.954 --> 01:47:28.435
or entity extraction, things like that, as far as I've seen, those are incredibly easy

01:47:28.435 --> 01:47:30.515
tasks for these LLMs.

01:47:30.555 --> 01:47:37.115
So for that kind of thing, I wouldn't be surprised if even the ones that run on your MacBook

01:47:37.115 --> 01:47:44.154
are pretty good, or that can run on a laptop are pretty decent.

01:47:44.154 --> 01:47:50.474
If you're doing it in bulk, it might be slow, but what are you going to do?

01:47:50.474 --> 01:47:57.034
So yeah, for NLP stuff, again, I'm far from an expert, but I found these things to be

01:47:57.034 --> 01:47:58.834
really surprisingly good.

01:47:58.834 --> 01:48:05.115
And not just good, but so easy compared to traditional NLP techniques, so easy and flexible.

01:48:05.115 --> 01:48:12.515
Okay, so I guess the last one we'll talk about is DeepSeq, just because it made a really

01:48:12.515 --> 01:48:15.154
big splash earlier this year.

01:48:15.154 --> 01:48:17.555
It is an open-weight model.

01:48:17.555 --> 01:48:20.234
It is Chinese.

01:48:20.234 --> 01:48:28.875
So there are some, I guess there's some censorship applied that reflects the values of the Chinese

