It really, I think, made really big news, because they used some optimizations when

01:48:42.995 --> 01:48:49.794
training it that were unprecedented and resulted in a really surprisingly cheap training run

01:48:50.075 --> 01:48:52.115
supposedly.

01:48:52.115 --> 01:48:56.555
That being said, I have personally not found it to be super awesome.

01:48:56.555 --> 01:49:02.555
I have not been able to use it to replace Claude for any of the demos that I have used.

01:49:02.555 --> 01:49:04.195
Same thing with Llama.

01:49:04.195 --> 01:49:07.515
And that's why I'm a little bit skeptical of all the benchmarks out there, because they

01:49:07.515 --> 01:49:14.234
say that, you know, every new model just crushes the competition, and then most of the time

01:49:14.234 --> 01:49:18.274
you go to use some new model and be like, this doesn't work for whatever I'm using it

01:49:18.274 --> 01:49:19.274
for.

01:49:19.274 --> 01:49:30.794
All right, that's all I'm going to say about models for today.

01:49:30.794 --> 01:49:36.995
Again, I encourage you to, if you're getting started with these things, if you're getting

01:49:36.995 --> 01:49:41.834
started playing with LLMs and you're prototyping, start with the best models that you have access

01:49:41.834 --> 01:49:42.834
to.

01:49:42.834 --> 01:49:50.714
I encourage you to not be distracted or worse, develop a false intuition for what the state

01:49:50.714 --> 01:49:58.875
of the art is in LLMs by using models that are just not close to the state of the art.

01:49:58.875 --> 01:50:04.834
And by all means, if people here have experience that's contrary to what I just said, please,

01:50:04.834 --> 01:50:09.834
I'm always interested to hear more data, more anecdotes.

01:50:10.834 --> 01:50:12.034
All right.

01:50:12.034 --> 01:50:15.914
So we talked a little bit about system prompts before, and we customized it to make it speak

01:50:15.914 --> 01:50:18.794
in Japanese or do whatever fun things.

01:50:18.794 --> 01:50:23.875
So let's dive more deeply into that.

01:50:23.875 --> 01:50:30.435
Let's talk in general about customizing behavior and adding knowledge to these LLMs.

01:50:30.435 --> 01:50:34.354
So the problem is one of two things, or both.

01:50:34.354 --> 01:50:39.515
The first being maybe you want to customize how the LLM responds.

01:50:39.555 --> 01:50:45.154
So the example I gave earlier was to say, don't be as verbose as you usually are.

01:50:45.154 --> 01:50:50.995
But you also might want to say, don't talk about these topics.

01:50:50.995 --> 01:50:52.555
These topics are off limits.

01:50:52.555 --> 01:50:57.674
Or focus narrowly on answering these kinds of questions and refuse to answer anything

01:50:57.674 --> 01:50:58.674
else.

01:50:58.674 --> 01:51:04.955
Or you might say, you know, we know these LLMs have a tendency to be overly agreeable

01:51:04.995 --> 01:51:05.995
sometimes.

01:51:05.995 --> 01:51:11.274
So you can say, like, be critical of both, you know, my thoughts and my questions, whatever.

01:51:11.274 --> 01:51:19.195
Like I really am looking for you to be to provide pushback and to challenge my ideas.

01:51:19.195 --> 01:51:23.674
And as we'll see, you can even have much more dramatic customizations where you're saying,

01:51:23.674 --> 01:51:25.234
like, I don't even want words back.

01:51:25.234 --> 01:51:30.555
I want JSON or I want, you know, what have you.

01:51:30.555 --> 01:51:37.395
For data analysis scenarios, we might say, when I ask you data questions, please answer

01:51:37.395 --> 01:51:38.955
using R code.

01:51:38.955 --> 01:51:41.854
Like not Python code, but R code.

01:51:41.854 --> 01:51:44.315
And not base R code, but tidyverse R code.

01:51:44.315 --> 01:51:45.315
Or whatever it is.

01:51:45.315 --> 01:51:49.034
Like, you can ask it for exactly what you want.

01:51:49.034 --> 01:51:55.034
Secondly, you might have the LLM you might want to use an LLM to answer questions, but

01:51:55.034 --> 01:51:59.395
it does not have the knowledge that it needs to either answer these questions or carry

01:51:59.395 --> 01:52:01.274
out whatever tasks you need it to.

01:52:01.274 --> 01:52:06.515
It might be because you have information that is needed that is too recent.

01:52:06.515 --> 01:52:10.075
Arguably, like, the weather data is something like that.

01:52:10.075 --> 01:52:12.354
That's definitely not going to be part of its training set.

01:52:12.354 --> 01:52:15.395
Or it could be information that's too specific.

01:52:15.395 --> 01:52:22.195
Like you're really getting into the nitty gritty of some particular, you know, like,

01:52:22.195 --> 01:52:27.354
some very detailed facts about some public figure and you want to, like, dive deep into

01:52:27.354 --> 01:52:28.354
that.

01:52:28.354 --> 01:52:34.234
Or, you know, facts about I don't know, like, we want to talk about Paris landmarks, but

01:52:34.234 --> 01:52:39.435
we have a very specific ranking that we want to be basing it off of.

01:52:39.435 --> 01:52:41.115
Or information that's private.

01:52:41.115 --> 01:52:45.034
Information that would never be part of the training set of an LLM.

01:52:45.034 --> 01:52:53.995
For example, like, I we want to take our marketing data or our customer data or, you know, God

01:52:53.995 --> 01:52:58.234
forbid, your patient data and give it access to that.

01:52:58.234 --> 01:53:01.995
There's no possible way that's part of this training set.

01:53:01.995 --> 01:53:10.435
So in both of these examples, we have a number of possible strategies for customizing or

01:53:10.435 --> 01:53:18.714
augmenting the knowledge of these LLMs.

01:53:18.714 --> 01:53:23.615
Beth says I've had answers come back using older versions of R packages because there's

01:53:23.734 --> 01:53:25.414
more info on the web for older syntax.

01:53:25.414 --> 01:53:31.734
So that's a great example of, like, we might want to use the latest features of dplyr or

01:53:31.734 --> 01:53:33.895
whatever, but that's information that's too recent.

01:53:33.895 --> 01:53:36.815
So let's talk about that a little bit later.

01:53:36.815 --> 01:53:39.034
There are solutions to that.

01:53:39.034 --> 01:53:42.534
So there are three main solutions we're going to talk about.

01:53:42.534 --> 01:53:45.214
There's actually a fourth that I forgot to add to this list.

01:53:45.214 --> 01:53:49.575
There's prompt engineering, which is a fancy way of saying customize the system prompt.

01:53:49.575 --> 01:53:52.774
There's retrieval augmented generation and there's fine tuning.

01:53:52.774 --> 01:53:55.375
And there's a fourth called agentic search.

01:53:55.375 --> 01:53:57.815
So let's focus on prompt engineering first.

01:53:57.815 --> 01:54:00.534
And we're going to spend a bunch of time on this.

01:54:00.534 --> 01:54:06.895
How do we customize the system prompt in order to direct the behavior and output of these

01:54:06.895 --> 01:54:08.695
models?

01:54:08.695 --> 01:54:13.815
So just some examples of ways we might that we commonly prompt these models.

01:54:13.815 --> 01:54:16.695
We say respond with just the minimal information necessary.

01:54:16.695 --> 01:54:19.375
Or we say think through this step by step.

01:54:19.375 --> 01:54:22.255
Or carefully read and follow these instructions.

01:54:22.854 --> 01:54:30.495
It's weird that this in at some level we are talking about computer software and yet things

01:54:30.495 --> 01:54:32.575
like this matter.

01:54:32.575 --> 01:54:35.174
Like telling it to like but really think before you answer.

01:54:35.174 --> 01:54:37.395
It actually makes a difference.

01:54:37.395 --> 01:54:41.334
Or saying like carefully read and follow these instructions.

01:54:41.334 --> 01:54:46.935
Studies have shown this does sometimes improve adherence to instructions for some models.

01:54:46.935 --> 01:54:49.654
Like I said, you can ask it to do R if you want.

01:54:49.654 --> 01:54:53.135
Be careful to only like don't hallucinate.

01:54:53.135 --> 01:54:55.414
This doesn't it's not fully effective.

01:54:55.414 --> 01:54:57.055
But it doesn't do nothing.

01:54:57.055 --> 01:55:00.135
It's kind of surprising.

01:55:00.135 --> 01:55:03.414
Raymond says play the role of a blank helps.

01:55:03.414 --> 01:55:04.414
Yes.

01:55:04.414 --> 01:55:05.414
Yeah.

01:55:05.414 --> 01:55:06.414
Absolutely.

01:55:06.414 --> 01:55:09.995
By the way, really interesting.

01:55:09.995 --> 01:55:14.094
Respond with just the minimal information necessary or be a terse assistant.

01:55:14.094 --> 01:55:17.495
It actually turns I didn't know this at the time that we put this presentation together.

01:55:17.495 --> 01:55:20.895
It actually makes the answers worse in a lot of cases.

01:55:20.895 --> 01:55:28.414
It's like the act of speaking helps the the act of speaking during inference time, it

01:55:28.414 --> 01:55:32.575
actually helps the model give more accurate answers.

01:55:32.575 --> 01:55:33.854
Which is pretty mind blowing.

01:55:33.854 --> 01:55:38.935
Maybe I'll add some slides about that for the next time I do this.

01:55:38.935 --> 01:55:40.455
So we're going to walk through this a little bit.

01:55:40.455 --> 01:55:48.255
We're going to give a specific non-trivial example of we want to take a plain text natural

01:55:48.255 --> 01:55:52.135
language recipe and we want to turn it into something structured.

01:55:52.135 --> 01:55:58.495
We want to extract an ingredient list out of this and return it in a structured format.

01:55:58.495 --> 01:56:01.094
So let's say this is the user input that comes in.

01:56:01.094 --> 01:56:08.775
And let's say the first our first attempt at the system prompt is just to say the user

01:56:08.775 --> 01:56:13.574
input contains recipe, extract a list of ingredients and return it in JSON format and

01:56:13.574 --> 01:56:16.574
we get this.

01:56:16.574 --> 01:56:19.495
So number one, like it did do it, right?

01:56:19.495 --> 01:56:23.135
This is JSON, it is the ingredients in that recipe.

01:56:23.135 --> 01:56:25.535
So like great job, kudos.

01:56:25.535 --> 01:56:29.734
That was not a lot of effort for us to go from plain text to structured.

01:56:29.734 --> 01:56:35.495
But if you look closer at this, like there are some I mean, like this is maybe not that

01:56:35.535 --> 01:56:38.974
helpful if we were going to do something programmatic with this data.

01:56:38.974 --> 01:56:45.094
Like if we were to format a recipe card, often we want the number or the units to be formatted

01:56:45.094 --> 01:56:48.175
differently than the item or something like that.

01:56:48.175 --> 01:56:50.495
So let's take another attempt at this.

01:56:50.495 --> 01:56:54.775
Let's be more specific about what we're asking, what we wanted to generate.

01:56:54.775 --> 01:56:58.974
So this time we say extract a list of ingredients and return it in JSON format.

01:56:58.974 --> 01:57:04.094
It should be an array of objects where each object has keys, ingredient, quantity, and

01:57:04.094 --> 01:57:07.854
unit, and then put each object on one line of output.

01:57:07.854 --> 01:57:09.734
And it did do that, okay?

01:57:09.734 --> 01:57:13.175
So ingredient, unsalted butter, quantity one, unit, cup.

01:57:13.175 --> 01:57:16.214
So that actually worked.

01:57:16.214 --> 01:57:22.015
In this example, if you look closer, there are actually a couple of weird things happening

01:57:22.015 --> 01:57:23.255
here.

01:57:23.255 --> 01:57:26.775
Number one, quantity of one half.

01:57:26.775 --> 01:57:28.295
This is not valid JSON.

01:57:28.295 --> 01:57:32.135
Like if you tried to parse this, this would actually fail.

01:57:32.135 --> 01:57:38.734
You can say 0.5, but like 1 over 2 is not valid JSON.

01:57:38.734 --> 01:57:42.535
And for the egg, it gave unit large.

01:57:42.535 --> 01:57:47.415
Like what is a large?

01:57:47.415 --> 01:57:50.334
So it's unclear why it decided to do that.

01:57:50.334 --> 01:57:56.175
And then here for the unit, like it's cup, singular here, it's cups, plural here, unclear

01:57:56.175 --> 01:58:00.495
whether that's what we would want, okay?

01:58:00.934 --> 01:58:06.814
Our third attempt at this, we are saying extract a list of ingredients and return in JSON format,

01:58:06.814 --> 01:58:09.175
and then let me just give you an example of what I want.

01:58:09.175 --> 01:58:15.135
So this text example output and then this code block, this is part of the system prompt.

01:58:15.135 --> 01:58:20.574
And it's really important to note, like this is extremely effective for LLMs.

01:58:20.574 --> 01:58:24.454
It is extremely effective to give them just an example of what you want.

01:58:24.454 --> 01:58:29.214
And often, if you give them an example and you give them instructions, and the instructions

01:58:29.214 --> 01:58:37.175
and the example disagree, they conflict, often it's more likely to adhere to the example.

01:58:37.175 --> 01:58:39.734
That's how powerful examples are.

01:58:39.734 --> 01:58:43.854
And that's like a little bit surprising, but not that surprising, because think about humans.

01:58:43.854 --> 01:58:48.775
Like if we have documentation that disagrees with the example, 9 times out of 10, I think

01:58:48.775 --> 01:58:51.375
people end up using the example.

01:58:51.375 --> 01:59:03.415
So I really think it's my best advice for this entire workshop is this.

01:59:03.415 --> 01:59:08.615
If you are trying to system prompt your way into a certain kind of behavior or a certain

01:59:08.615 --> 01:59:15.214
kind of outcome and it's not working, I would ask you three questions in this order.

01:59:15.214 --> 01:59:18.574
Number one, are you using the best models?

01:59:18.574 --> 01:59:25.574
Are you using GPT-4.1 or CLAWD-4, SONNET, or, you know, O3 or O4 Mini?

01:59:25.574 --> 01:59:27.814
Are you using the best models?

01:59:27.814 --> 01:59:34.734
Number two, does your system prompt say what you're looking for?

01:59:34.734 --> 01:59:39.895
Like are you telling the model what you want or are you relying on it to just guess what

01:59:39.895 --> 01:59:42.175
kind of answer you're looking for?

01:59:42.175 --> 01:59:46.255
And number three, if you've described what you're looking for and it's not giving you

01:59:46.415 --> 01:59:50.135
those kinds of responses, have you provided an example?

01:59:50.135 --> 01:59:52.615
So number one, are you using the best model?

01:59:52.615 --> 01:59:56.015
Number two, have you told the model in the system prompt what you want?

01:59:56.015 --> 01:59:58.854
And number three, did you give it an example?

01:59:58.854 --> 02:00:05.694
And a surprising amount of time, just by doing those three things, these models, you can

02:00:05.694 --> 02:00:13.415
go from failure to success.

02:00:13.415 --> 02:00:20.974
So that covers kind of talking about tailoring the behavior, customizing the behavior of

02:00:20.974 --> 02:00:21.974
these models.

02:00:21.974 --> 02:00:27.415
And you're saying, like, act in this way, give me results in this style.

02:00:27.415 --> 02:00:33.734
So let's shift gears a little bit and talk about adding new context or new knowledge

02:00:33.734 --> 02:00:34.974
to the prompt.

02:00:34.974 --> 02:00:39.375
So using the system prompt not to tell it what to do, but to give it more information

02:00:39.375 --> 02:00:41.995
about the problem space that you're dealing with.

02:00:41.995 --> 02:00:46.434
So some examples of ways we might do this, we might take documentation files and add

02:00:46.434 --> 02:00:47.434
it to the prompt.

02:00:47.434 --> 02:00:53.515
Like I said earlier, Elmer is too early for chat GPT to know how to work with it or even

02:00:53.515 --> 02:00:54.515
what it is.

02:00:54.515 --> 02:00:57.035
So we created our own Elmer assistant.

02:00:57.035 --> 02:01:03.775
That is literally just a totally stock, you know, GPT 4.1 or whatever, except the system

02:01:03.775 --> 02:01:10.275
prompt is I pasted the readme from Elmer and from ShinyChat into the system prompt and

02:01:10.275 --> 02:01:14.194
said, like, here are a couple of readmes, answer questions about these packages, and

02:01:14.194 --> 02:01:18.035
it works really shockingly well.

02:01:18.035 --> 02:01:21.354
So adding documentation is one way to customize the prompt.

02:01:21.354 --> 02:01:24.155
Like I said, add positive examples.

02:01:24.155 --> 02:01:32.035
Oh, at least in all the models that I've used so far, they're all really like it's very

02:01:32.035 --> 02:01:35.194
helpful to add examples of what you want.

02:01:35.194 --> 02:01:39.495
And much less helpful to add examples of what you don't want.

02:01:39.714 --> 02:01:45.995
So to say, like, yes, give me responses like this, no, don't give me responses like this,

02:01:45.995 --> 02:01:51.535
the negative examples don't they often don't work well and in fact are often counterproductive.

02:01:51.535 --> 02:01:57.574
So try to frame everything in terms of positive examples.

02:01:57.574 --> 02:02:00.655
And if you're really tempted to put in, like, a negative example, like, go ahead and try

02:02:00.655 --> 02:02:05.035
it, but if it doesn't do what you want, try adding a few more positive examples that don't

02:02:05.035 --> 02:02:08.615
exhibit whatever the negative example is going to exhibit.

02:02:08.615 --> 02:02:13.974
It is important to note that, like I said, every model has its limits for how much information

02:02:13.974 --> 02:02:14.974
can fit inside.

02:02:14.974 --> 02:02:19.934
So you're going to be limited to whatever docs can fit in that window.

02:02:19.934 --> 02:02:25.615
And then here are some examples where you can see exactly, like, the kinds of information

02:02:25.615 --> 02:02:26.694
that was stuffed into a prompt.

02:02:26.694 --> 02:02:28.334
So this is the Elmer assistant.

02:02:28.334 --> 02:02:32.655
You can see here, I literally said, like, here is the readme.

02:02:32.655 --> 02:02:36.094
And, like, the rest of this is just, like, all of this is just going into the system

02:02:36.094 --> 02:02:37.094
prompt.

02:02:37.094 --> 02:02:38.094
Yeah.

