02:04:39.934 --> 02:04:44.814
Let's totally shift gears and talk about RAG, which stands for retrieval augmented

02:04:44.814 --> 02:04:46.655
generation.

02:04:46.655 --> 02:04:49.334
A lot of you have probably heard this term.

02:04:49.334 --> 02:04:54.415
I will say that there is some squishiness in the definition of this term.

02:04:54.415 --> 02:04:59.974
I'm going to give you what I want this definition to mean.

02:04:59.974 --> 02:05:01.615
Not everybody agrees with me.

02:05:01.615 --> 02:05:02.615
Some people agree with me.

02:05:02.615 --> 02:05:05.175
Not everybody does.

02:05:05.175 --> 02:05:09.255
But my definition, I think, is the most useful definition.

02:05:09.574 --> 02:05:13.454
I'll tell you what the other definition is as well when we finish this section.

02:05:13.454 --> 02:05:18.895
So RAG is a technique that's very useful when the documents you have don't fit into the

02:05:18.895 --> 02:05:19.895
context window.

02:05:19.895 --> 02:05:23.655
Like, you have a lot of information that would be great if you could just stick it in the

02:05:23.655 --> 02:05:27.214
system prompt, but it won't fit.

02:05:27.214 --> 02:05:29.615
Or it's too expensive to do that.

02:05:29.615 --> 02:05:35.054
So what this does instead is when the user sends a query to an app saying, like, how

02:05:35.054 --> 02:05:42.135
do I do this or that, and you're pretty much designed the bot to be able to answer, like,

02:05:42.135 --> 02:05:47.375
this question that generally could not be answered without additional information.

02:05:47.375 --> 02:05:56.214
So the application, meaning the chat bot, before it sends a request to the LLM, it will

02:05:56.214 --> 02:06:02.015
go and find some related information from the docs that it has in hand via some kind

02:06:02.015 --> 02:06:05.295
of search.

02:06:05.295 --> 02:06:12.655
And it will come up with some hits from its search, and it will combine those hits with

02:06:12.655 --> 02:06:15.334
the question asked by the user.

02:06:15.334 --> 02:06:17.934
You can think of it as being, like, oh, you asked me a question.

02:06:17.934 --> 02:06:20.375
I'm about to pass that question to an expert.

02:06:20.375 --> 02:06:25.775
But first I'm going to do a Google search and include the results of that Google search

02:06:25.775 --> 02:06:31.415
along with the question and send all of that to the expert so that the expert has this

02:06:31.415 --> 02:06:35.974
additional information if they want to consult it.

02:06:35.974 --> 02:06:39.094
So what is this search?

02:06:39.094 --> 02:06:41.814
What is this usually?

02:06:41.814 --> 02:06:45.934
For whatever reason, the prevalent technique this could be anything.

02:06:45.934 --> 02:06:47.454
It could be a simple keyword search.

02:06:47.454 --> 02:06:55.974
It could be using whatever traditional search engine technology we've had up to this time.

02:06:56.135 --> 02:07:01.454
For whatever reason, in the LLM, what's been very fashionable is using a vector database.

02:07:01.454 --> 02:07:04.454
So it doesn't really matter what this is.

02:07:04.454 --> 02:07:08.495
Just suffice it to say, it is not doing a simple match of the exact word that you searched

02:07:08.495 --> 02:07:10.535
for being in the documentation.

02:07:10.535 --> 02:07:16.135
It looks for the general meaning of the word and will also match on concepts that are nearby.

02:07:16.135 --> 02:07:22.574
So the result, though, is that the application will issue some kind of query to some kind

02:07:22.574 --> 02:07:29.214
of system, get some kind of chunks of text back, and then include that text with the

02:07:29.214 --> 02:07:33.054
question when it sends it to the LLM, okay?

02:07:33.054 --> 02:07:38.655
So the LLM only has access to the chunks that were passed in by the app.

02:07:38.655 --> 02:07:44.814
It does not have access to the rest of the documentation, okay?

02:07:44.814 --> 02:07:48.255
Can we have a live showcase of this?

02:07:48.255 --> 02:07:50.934
Sure.

