02:11:27.015 --> 02:11:34.015
So there is one final technique that is different than RAG, called agentic search.

02:11:34.015 --> 02:11:36.015
Do I have another slide on this?

02:11:36.015 --> 02:11:37.015
No.

02:11:38.015 --> 02:11:39.015
Okay.

02:11:39.015 --> 02:11:40.015
So agentic search.

02:11:39.767 --> 02:11:50.767
Okay, yes. So it's similar to RAG in that it is a way of providing extra information to the LLM, but it's different than RAG in that

02:11:42.156 --> 02:11:49.316
RAG in that we don't have the application that surrounds the LLM doing the search and

02:11:49.316 --> 02:11:55.836
sending the LLM the information that it found. Instead, it starts with just sending the information

02:11:55.836 --> 02:12:01.916
to sending, sorry, with agentic search, you're sending the question to the LLM and providing

02:12:01.916 --> 02:12:09.035
a tool that the LLM can use to perform a search if it wants to. Okay. So, like, the difference

02:12:09.035 --> 02:12:17.996
here is with RAG, the code that calls the LLM is preemptively doing a search on the LLM's behalf

02:12:18.876 --> 02:12:25.915
using whatever search criteria it decided, whereas when you put control with agentic search,

02:12:25.915 --> 02:12:30.075
you're putting control into the LLM's hands to say, like, I don't know if you want to make a

02:12:30.075 --> 02:12:33.516
search or if you want to make a search what search terms you're going to use, but here's a tool that

02:12:33.516 --> 02:12:44.316
you can use to do that if and when you decide to. And that has a number of advantages. Number one,

02:12:44.876 --> 02:12:52.956
it avoids this sort of needless waste of doing preemptive searches that it might not even be

02:12:52.956 --> 02:13:00.316
needed. Secondly, it's possible that the appropriate search term has very little

02:13:00.316 --> 02:13:06.316
resemblance to the actual user prompt. Like, it might be that the term that would be useful for

02:13:06.316 --> 02:13:09.995
producing good results is something that's obvious to a human and obvious to an LLM,

02:13:09.995 --> 02:13:17.276
but not obvious to whatever deterministic code is surrounding the LLM and performing this search.

02:13:17.755 --> 02:13:26.956
Okay. And number three, it gives the LLM the ability to decide, like, oh, these search

02:13:26.956 --> 02:13:33.276
results did not answer my question. Let me try a different query or let me

02:13:34.156 --> 02:13:41.916
fetch more results for this particular query. So those are the benefits. The downside is

02:13:43.035 --> 02:13:49.035
because the search has to be initiated by the LLM and then the LLM has to retrieve the response,

02:13:49.035 --> 02:13:56.316
it is slower and more expensive than just letting the search be done preemptively and

02:13:56.316 --> 02:14:04.715
included in one single interaction. Okay. So agentic search and RAG, RAG is like your

02:14:04.715 --> 02:14:11.676
force feeding hits, search result hits into the model, and then agentic search is you're

02:14:11.676 --> 02:14:17.355
giving the model the ability to pull information from the outside world into itself. All right.

02:14:18.316 --> 02:14:21.116
Any questions about RAG versus agentic search?

02:14:25.596 --> 02:14:29.995
I complained earlier about, like, RAG doesn't mean the same thing to everybody,

02:14:29.995 --> 02:14:35.355
and what I'm really basically what it comes down to, what I'm calling agentic search,

02:14:35.355 --> 02:14:43.596
some people refer to this as RAG as well. So both when you are force feeding search results to the

02:14:43.596 --> 02:14:48.715
LLM and when the LLM has the ability to go perform a search, some people refer to both

02:14:48.715 --> 02:14:53.596
of those as RAG, which I find really frustrating because the distinction is interesting and

02:14:53.596 --> 02:15:01.676
important. Glenda asked, RAG may have some promise in medical when the corpus or repository changes

02:15:01.676 --> 02:15:06.715
over time and needs to be isolated. For example, an accumulating patient record. Yeah, totally.

02:15:07.676 --> 02:15:14.876
Let's talk about the opposite of that. Let's talk about fine-tuning. So fine-tuning it,

02:15:14.876 --> 02:15:18.075
oh, actually, let's go back and see if our RAG thing is done. Hey!

02:15:21.676 --> 02:15:27.995
Okay. What are the benefits of our cloud storage solution? Oh, yawn. Okay. But let's let it run

02:15:27.995 --> 02:15:33.756
that. So it's saying, okay, it found some hits. These hits are scored at different amounts.

02:15:36.715 --> 02:15:39.835
Combining the user question with retrieved context.

02:15:43.195 --> 02:15:48.715
Why is it going so slowly? Okay. So you can see here that what it's going to pass to

02:15:49.756 --> 02:15:54.555
the model includes all of these documents. Oh, this is infuriating that this is

02:15:56.236 --> 02:16:00.636
simulated latency and yet it went so slow. Okay. We'll come back to that again.

02:16:01.196 --> 02:16:10.316
So fine-tuning is where we take an existing model and we provide new information to retrain the

02:16:10.316 --> 02:16:18.876
model and come up with a new version with updated weights. Okay. So not all models can be fine-tuned.

02:16:20.156 --> 02:16:28.156
The open weights ones like LLAMA and DeepSeq tend to be fine-tunable. And some of the proprietary

02:16:29.115 --> 02:16:34.955
ones, they'll provide an API where you provide the fine-tuning data and then they will, without

02:16:34.955 --> 02:16:39.515
giving you access to the model directly, they will create a fine-tuned version of it for you

02:16:39.515 --> 02:16:44.796
and make that available via API. Okay. That sounds great. That sounds very exciting. Like, oh,

02:16:44.796 --> 02:16:49.115
why don't we just make the model better? A couple of problems with that. Number one,

02:16:50.076 --> 02:16:55.515
the data must be provided in a very specific format. It has to be in the form of a question

02:16:55.515 --> 02:17:04.796
and answer. So I could not just take the Elmer docs and say, please fine-tune GBT 401 using the

02:17:04.796 --> 02:17:12.476
Elmer docs. No, you have to construct a set of question and answers. And from what I've been

02:17:12.476 --> 02:17:23.036
told, you do need thousands of examples, thousands of these sort of query and response pairs to be

02:17:23.036 --> 02:17:29.675
able to make it reliable. More recently, I heard someone say, no, it can be as few as a couple

02:17:29.675 --> 02:17:40.636
hundred. But regardless, it's more effort. It also takes a long time to do fine-tuning. And

02:17:41.275 --> 02:17:45.115
with fine-tuning, every time there's new information that you need to update the model

02:17:45.115 --> 02:17:51.515
with, you need to go through this fine-tuning exercise again. So suffice it to say, it's really

02:17:51.515 --> 02:17:58.636
expensive and not a very dynamic process, and also, at the end of the day, less reliable

02:17:59.756 --> 02:18:10.235
in changing the behavior than the other two. So my best advice to you is to start with prompting,

02:18:11.275 --> 02:18:19.356
then shift to RAG and or agentic search, and only, if absolutely necessary, turn to fine-tuning.

02:18:19.356 --> 02:18:28.555
I will modify this to say this is definitely, I'm mostly talking about small-scale usage or

02:18:28.555 --> 02:18:36.796
for prototyping. If you have an LLM model that you are deploying at scale, I mean,

02:18:36.796 --> 02:18:41.515
probably not in the context of R medicine, but if you're a startup and your whole business is

02:18:41.515 --> 02:18:48.156
serving up this model to millions of users and you really care about maximizing the cost per query,

02:18:48.156 --> 02:18:53.275
